Definition 1.15. A map $f$ in a restriction category $\mathbf{X}$ is called total whenever $\overline{f}=1.$
Definition 2.1. Let $A$ be an object of a restriction category $\mathbf{X}.$ Let $E_{A}$ denote the set of restrictions of all endomorphisms on $A.$ That is, $E_{A}=\left\{\overline{f_{A}}:A\rightarrow A|f:A\rightarrow A\in\mathbf{X}% \right\}.$
Definition 1.1. A groupoid $(G,\circ)$ is said to be an ordered groupoid whenever there is a partial order $\leq$ on its arrows satisfying the following four conditions: (i) For each arrow $f,g\in G,$ $f\leq g$ implies $f^{-1}\leq g^{-1}.$ (ii) For each arrow $a,A,b,B\in G$ such that $a\leq A,$ $b\leq B$ and the composites $ab$ and $AB$ exist, then $ab\leq AB.$ (iii) For each arrow $f:A^{\prime}\rightarrow B$ in $G$ and objects $A\leq A^{\prime}$ in $G,$ there exists a unique restriction of $f$ to $A$, denoted $[f|_{*}A],$ such that $\mathrm{dom}[f|_{*}A]=A$ and $[f|_{*}A]\leq f.$ (iv) For each arrow $f:A\rightarrow B^{\prime}$ in $G$ and objects $B\leq B^{\prime}$ in $G,$ there exists a unique corestriction of $f$ to $B$, denoted $[B\,{}_{*}|f],$ such that $\mathrm{cod}[B\,{}_{*}|f]=B$ and $[B\,{}_{*}|f]\leq f.$ An ordered groupoid is said to be an inductive groupoid whenever its objects form a meet-semilattice.
Definition 1.17. A morphism $F:\mathbf{X}\rightarrow\mathbf{Y}$ of restriction categories (a restriction functor) is a functor such that $F\left(\overline{f}\right)=\overline{F(f)}$ for each $f\in X_{1}.$
Definition 2.5. An ordered groupoid is said to be a locally inductive groupoid whenever there is a partition $\{M_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ of $\mathbf{G}_{0}$ into meet-semilattices $M_{i}$ with the property that any two comparable objects be in the same meet-semilattice $M_{i}.$ A locally inductive groupoid is said to be top-heavy whenever each meet-semilattice $M_{i}$ admits a top-element $\top_{i}.$
Definition 1.10. A category $\mathbf{X}$ is said to be an inverse category whenever, for each arrow $f:A\rightarrow B$ in $\mathbf{X},$ there exists a unique $f^{\circ}:B\rightarrow A$ in $\mathbf{X}$ such that $f\circ f^{\circ}\circ f=f$ and $f^{\circ}\circ f\circ f^{\circ}=f^{\circ}.$
Definition 1.6. A morphism $F:\mathbf{G}\rightarrow\mathbf{H}$ of ordered groupoids (an ordered functor) is a functor such that, for all arrows $f\leq g$ in $\mathbf{G},$ $F(f)\leq F(g)$ in $\mathbf{H}.$ An ordered functor between inductive groupoids is said to be inductive whenever it preserves the meet structure on objects.
Definition 1.20. A restriction category $\mathbf{X}$ is called an inverse category, whenever every map $f$ is a restricted isomorphism.
Definition 1.3. Let $\mathbf{G}$ be an ordered groupoid with arrows $\alpha,\beta\in\mathbf{G}.$ If $\mathrm{dom}(\alpha)\wedge\mathrm{cod}(\beta)$ exists, the tensor product $\alpha\otimes\beta$ of $\alpha$ and $\beta$ is defined as $\alpha\otimes\beta=[\alpha\,|_{*}\,\mathrm{dom}(\alpha)\wedge\mathrm{cod}(% \beta)][\mathrm{dom}(\alpha)\wedge\mathrm{cod}(\beta)\,{}_{*}|\,\beta].$
Definition 2.3. The $R$-linearization of $C$, which we will denote by $RC$, is the category with the same objects as $C$ and whose hom-objects are free $R$-modules on the hom-sets of $C$ $RC(c,c^{\prime})=\bigoplus_{f\in C(c,c^{\prime})}Rf,$ with the obvious composition rule. In other words, $RC$ is the free $R$-linear category on $C$.
Definition 2.5. If $D$ is an $R$-linear category, then the category of right $C$-modules over $R$ is defined to be the functor category $\mathrm{Mod}_{R}D=\mathrm{Fun}_{R}(D,\mathrm{Mod}_{R})$ of $R$-linear functors.
Definition 2.1. The category of right $C$-modules over $R$ is the functor category $\operatorname{Mod}_{R}C=\mathrm{Fun}(C^{\mathrm{op}},\operatorname{Mod}R)$ consisting of contravariant functors from $C$ to the category of $R$-modules.
Definition 2.4. An $R$-linear category $D$ is a small category enriched in $R$-modules. It is flat if $D(c,c^{\prime})$ is a flat $R$-module for all pairs of objects $c,c^{\prime}$ in $D$.
Definition 5.3. We call a function $\sigma\colon\operatorname{Spec}R\to\mathrm{NC}(Q)$ specialization closed if whenever $p\subseteq q$ we have $\sigma(p)\leq\sigma(q)$ in $\mathrm{NC}(Q)$.
Definition 3.2. Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a poset. An interval in $\mathcal{P}$ is a subset $I\subseteq\mathcal{P}$ such that whenever $x,y\in I$ and $x<z<y$, we have $z\in I$. If $\mathcal{P}$ is any poset, then we denote by $\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{P}}$ be the poset of intervals in $\mathcal{P}$ ordered by inclusion. If $I$ and $J$ are a pair of intervals, we’ll write $I\prec J$ if there is no pair $(i\in I,j\in J)$ with $i>j$.
Definition 3.20. Let $\mathbb{P}^{m}(\mathcal{P})$ be the subset of $\mathbb{P}^{\prime}(\mathcal{P})$ containing those sets $T=\{I_{1},\cdots,I_{k}\}$ such that for each $I_{i}$, either $|I_{i}|=1$ or $I_{i}=\mathcal{P}_{\leq i}\text{ for some }i\leq m.$ In particular, at most one of the $I_{i}$ may have cardinality $>1$, and if this occurs then $I_{i}$ must be a $\prec$-minimal element of $T$.
Definition 2.20. We define the geometric value at $\mathcal{N}$ functor $\Phi^{\mathcal{N}}:\mathbf{Mack}(\mathcal{M},\mathbf{C})\to\mathbf{Mack}(% \mathcal{N},\mathbf{C})$ by the left Kan extension $(A^{eff}(j_{\mathcal{N}}))_{!}$. Since left Kan extensions of additive functors along additive functors are additive, this definition makes sense. The right adjoint of $\Phi^{\mathcal{N}}$, the extension by zero from $\mathcal{N}$ functor, will be denoted $\Xi^{\mathcal{N}}$. For an object $X$ of $\mathcal{M}$, we’ll denote $\Phi^{\mathcal{M}_{\leq X}}$ by $\Phi^{X}$. If $E$ is an object of $\mathbf{Mack}(\mathcal{M},\mathbf{C})$, then we’ll write $E^{\Phi X}$ for the value of $\Phi^{X}E$ on $X$, the “geometric fixed point spectrum at $X$”.
Definition A.3. Let $\mathcal{L}(G)$ be the Lawvere theory of commutative monoids with $G$-action: the full subcategory of $\text{Fun}(G,\bf{CMon})$, which is equivalent to $\bf{CMon}(\text{Fun}(G,\textbf{Top}))$, spanned by the the essential image of $\mathcal{F}\subseteq\textbf{Top}$ under the left adjoint of the forgetful functor $\text{Fun}(G,\bf{CMon})\to\textbf{Top}$.
Definition 3.15. Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a finite poset. Define $\mathbb{P}(\mathcal{P})$ to be the poset of nonempty subsets $T=\{i_{1},i_{2},\cdots,i_{k}\}$ of $\mathcal{P}$, ordered by reverse inclusion.
Definition 2.14. If $\mathcal{M}$ is a EOC, we’ll write $A^{eff}(\mathcal{M})$ for the effective Burnside category $A^{eff}(\mathcal{M}^{\amalg})$; we don’t expect this notation to cause confusion. $A^{eff}(\mathcal{M})$ admits direct sums, and if $\mathbf{C}$ is a presentable $\infty$-category which admits direct sums, then we’ll denote by $\mathbf{Mack}(\mathcal{M},\mathbf{C})$ the category of $\mathbf{C}$-valued Mackey functors on $\mathcal{M}$: the category of additive (i.e. direct-sum-preserving) functors from $\mathcal{M}$ to $\mathbf{C}$. If $\mathbf{C}=\textbf{Sp}$, then we’ll usually omit $\mathbf{C}$ and refer to the category simply as $\mathbf{Mack}(\mathcal{M})$.
Definition 3.18. Let $\mathbb{P}^{\prime}(\mathcal{P})$ be the set whose elements are nonempty sets $\{I_{1},\cdots,I_{k}\}$ of nonempty, disjoint intervals in $\mathcal{P}$ such that for each pair of indices $i,j$, either $I_{i}\prec I_{j}$ or $I_{j}\prec I_{i}$. We’ll put a partial order on $\mathbb{P}^{\prime}(\mathcal{P})$ by letting $\{I_{1},\cdots,I_{k}\}\geq\{J_{1},\cdots,J_{l}\}$ if there exist distinct indices $(i_{1},\cdots,i_{k})$ such that $J_{i_{j}}\subseteq I_{j}$ for each $j$.
Definition 2.26. The Taylor coefficient at $X$ functor is the functor $D^{X}:\mathbf{Mack}(\mathcal{M},\mathbf{C})\to\text{Fun}(\mathcal{G}_{X},% \mathbf{C})$ given by $i_{X}^{*}\circ\Phi^{X}$.
Definition 3.30. Suppose $0=\mathbf{C}_{0}\subseteq\mathbf{C}_{1}\subseteq\cdots\subseteq\mathbf{C}_{n}\subseteq\cdots$ is a sequence of stable $\infty$-categories such that $\mathbf{C}_{n-1}$ is a reflective stable subcategory of $\mathbf{C}_{n}$ for all $n$. Suppose we have, for each $n$, a stratification $\mathfrak{S}_{n}$ of $\mathbf{C}_{n}$ along $\mathcal{P}_{\leq n}$, and that all of these are compatible in the sense that $\mathbf{C}_{n-1}=\mathfrak{S}_{n}(\mathcal{P}_{\leq n-1})$ and $\mathfrak{S}_{n-1}$ is the induced stratification. Let $\mathbf{C}_{\infty}:=\underset{n}{\text{lim }}\mathbf{C}_{n}$ be the limit over the localization maps. We call this data a pro-stratification of $\mathbf{C}_{\infty}$ along $\mathcal{P}$.
Definition 3.4. With the above notation, let $\mathcal{L}_{I}:\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{C}$ be the localization functor corresponding to $\mathfrak{S}(I)$. Then we call $\mathfrak{S}$ a stratification of $\mathbf{C}$ along $\mathcal{P}$ if the following conditions hold: • $\mathfrak{S}(\mathcal{P})=\mathbf{C}$, and • if $I=I_{1}\coprod I_{2}$ with $I_{2}\prec I_{1}$, then the natural diagram $\tikzcd\mathcal{L}_{I}\ar{r}\ar{d}&\mathcal{L}_{I_{1}}\ar{d}\\ \mathcal{L}_{I_{2}}\ar{r}&\mathcal{L}_{I_{2}}\mathcal{L}_{I_{1}}$ is a pullback square.
Definition 2.1. A epiorbital category or EOC is an essentially finite category $\mathcal{M}$ satisfying the following condtions: • Every morphism in $\mathcal{M}$ is an epimorphism. • $\mathcal{M}$ admits pushouts and coequalizers; equivalently, $\mathcal{M}$ admits colimits over finite connected diagrams.
Definition 3.16. Let $(\mathbf{C},\mathfrak{S})$ be a stable $\infty$-category stratified along $\mathcal{P}$. We define an $\infty$-category $\mathbf{C}^{\mathfrak{S}}$ as the full subcategory of $\text{Fun}(\mathbb{P}(\mathcal{P}),\mathbf{C})$ spanned by those functors $F:\mathbb{P}(\mathcal{P})\to\mathbf{C}$ such that • for each $T\in\mathbb{P}(\mathcal{P})$ and for each minimal element $t\in T$, $F(T)$ is in $\mathfrak{S}(\{t\})$; • if $e$ is an edge of $\mathbb{P}(\mathcal{P})$ of the form $T\to T\cup\{p\}$ where $\{p\}\prec T$, then $F(e)$ exhibits $F(T\cup\{p\})$ as the $\mathfrak{S}(\{p\})$-localization of $F(T)$.
Definition 2.23. Let $A^{eff}(\mathcal{M}\setminus\mathcal{N})$ be the effective Burnside category of $(\mathcal{M}\setminus\mathcal{N})^{\amalg}$, or equivalently, the full subcategory of $A^{eff}(\mathcal{M})$ spanned by the objects of $(\mathcal{M}\setminus\mathcal{N})^{\amalg}$. Let $A^{eff}(i_{\mathcal{M}\setminus\mathcal{N}})$ be the inclusion of this full subcategory.
Definition 3.21. Let $\mathbf{C}^{\mathfrak{S}}_{m}$ be the full subcategory of $\text{Fun}(\mathbb{P}^{m}(\mathcal{P}))$ spanned by those functors $F:\mathbb{P}^{m}(\mathcal{P})\to\mathbf{C}$ such that • for each $T=\{I_{1},\cdots,I_{k}\}\in\mathbb{P}^{m}(\mathcal{P})$ and for each $I_{i}$ that is $\prec$-minimal in $T$, $F(T)\in\mathfrak{S}(I_{i})$; • if $e:T_{1}\to T_{2}$ is an edge of $\mathbb{P}^{m}(\mathcal{P})$ of the form $\{I_{1},I_{2},\cdots,I_{k}\}\to\{I_{1},I_{2},\cdots,J_{k}\}$ with $I_{k}$ $\prec$-minimal in $T_{1}$ and $J_{k}\subseteq I_{k}$, then $F(e)$ exhibits $F(T_{2})$ as the $\mathfrak{S}(J_{k})$-localization of $F(T_{1})$; • if $e:T_{1}\to T_{2}$ is an edge of $\mathbb{P}^{m}(\mathcal{P})$ of the form $\{I_{1},I_{2},\cdots,I_{k}\}\to\{I_{1},I_{2},\cdots,I_{k},I_{k+1}\}$ with $I_{k+1}$ $\prec$-minimal, then $F(e)$ exhibits $F(T_{2})$ as the $\mathfrak{S}(I_{k+1})$-localization of $F(T_{1})$.
Definition 2.10. An $\infty$-category $\mathbf{C}$ is called disjunctive if • $\mathbf{C}$ admits pullbacks and finite coproducts, • for each finite set $I$ and for each $I$-tuple $(X_{i})_{i\in I}$ of objects of $\mathbf{C}$, the natural functor $\prod_{i}\mathbf{C}_{/X_{i}}\to\mathbf{C}_{/\coprod_{i}X_{i}}$ is an equivalence of categories.
Definition 3.3. Suppose $\mathbf{C}$ is a stable $\infty$-category. Let $\mathcal{E}_{\mathbf{C}}$ be the poset of stable reflective subcategories of $\mathbf{C}$, ordered by inclusion; equivalently, $\mathcal{E}_{\mathbf{C}}$ is the opposite of the poset of exact localizations of $\mathbf{C}$. Let $\mathbf{P}$ be a poset. Then a pre-stratification of $\mathbf{C}$ along $\mathcal{P}$ is a map of posets $\mathfrak{S}:\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{P}}\to\mathcal{E}_{\mathbf{C}}.$
Definition A.2. [Lur12, Remark 2.4.2.2] Let $\mathbf{C}$ be an $\infty$-category which admits finite products. Recall that by definition, the category $\bf{CMon}(\mathbf{C})$ of commutative monoids in $\mathbf{C}$ is the full subcategory of $\text{Fun}(\mathcal{F}_{*},\mathbf{C})$ spanned by those functors $F$ satisfying the Segal condition: for each $S\in\mathcal{F}_{*}$, the edges $F(S)\to F(\{s\}_{+})$ determine an equivalence $F(S)\simeq\prod_{s\in S^{o}}F(\{s\}_{+}).$ We’ll abbreviate $\bf{CMon}(\textbf{Top})$ to $\bf{CMon}$.
Definition 2.27. Let $\mathcal{M}^{\sim}$ be the maximal subgroupoid of $\mathcal{M}$ and define the Taylor sequence functor $D:\mathbf{Mack}(\mathcal{M},\mathbf{C})\to\text{Fun}(\mathcal{M}^{\sim},% \mathbf{C})$ by $\bigvee_{[X]}D^{X}.$
Definition 3.19. A threading of a finite poset $\mathcal{P}$ is a filtration $\emptyset=\mathcal{P}_{\leq 0}\subseteq\mathcal{P}_{\leq 1}\subseteq\cdots% \mathcal{P}_{\leq n}=\mathcal{P}$ such that for each $i$, $\mathcal{P}_{\leq i}$ is downwardly closed, and $|\mathcal{P}_{\leq i}|=i.$
Definition 2.3. It follows immediately from Yoneda’s lemma that any endomorphism in a epiorbital category is an isomorphism, and so the set of isomorphism classes of objects of $\mathcal{M}$ carries a natural partial order wherein $[X]\geq[Y]$ if and only if the morphism set $\mathcal{M}(X,Y)$ is nonempty. We’ll call this poset $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}}$.
Definition 3.13. We define a pre-stratification $\mathfrak{S}_{\mathcal{M}}$ on $\mathbf{Mack}(\mathcal{M};\mathbf{C})$ as follows. If $I\subseteq\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}}$ is any interval, let $\mathcal{I}$ be the corresponding full subcategory of $\mathcal{M}$. If $I$ is downwardly-closed, then we define $\displaystyle\mathfrak{S}_{\mathcal{M}}(I)=\mathbf{Mack}_{\mathcal{I}}(% \mathcal{M};\mathbf{C})$ $\displaystyle(\text{Corollary \ref{mackn0}})$ If $J\subseteq\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}}$ is upwardly closed, then let $\mathbf{Mack}^{\mathcal{J}}(\mathcal{M},\mathbf{C})$ be the essential image of the right Kan extension $A^{eff}(i_{\mathcal{J}})_{*}:\mathbf{Mack}(\mathcal{J},\mathbf{C})\to\mathbf{% Mack}(\mathcal{M},\mathbf{C}).$ We define $\mathfrak{S}_{\mathcal{M}}(J)=\mathbf{Mack}^{\mathcal{J}}(\mathcal{M},\mathbf{% C}).$ If $I\subseteq\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}}$ is any interval, then we can write $I=I_{+}\cap I_{-}$ where $I_{+}$ is the smallest upwardly-closed set containing $I$ and $I_{-}$ is, likewise, the smallest downwardly-closed set containing $I$. Then we define $\mathfrak{S}_{\mathcal{M}}(I)=\mathbf{Mack}^{\mathcal{I}_{+}}(\mathcal{M},% \mathbf{C})\cap\mathbf{Mack}_{\mathcal{I}_{-}}(\mathcal{M},\mathbf{C}).$
Definition 2.2 (Morita extension, [Barrett]). Let $\mathbb{T}_{1}$ and $\mathbb{T}_{2}$ be coherent theories over signatures $\Sigma_{1}$ and $\Sigma_{2}$ respectively. We say that $\mathbb{T}_{2}$ is a Morita extension of $\mathbb{T}_{1}$ if $\mathbb{T}_{2}$ is a definitional extension of $\mathbb{T}_{1}$ and every symbol in $\Sigma_{2}\setminus\Sigma_{1}\textbf{-Sort}$ is either a product sort, a coproduct sort, a quotient sort or a subsort and $\mathbb{T}_{2}$ contains in each case the appropriate sequents as defined above.
Definition 2.4. We call two theories $\mathbb{T}$, $\mathbb{T}^{\prime}$ (over signatures $\Sigma$, $\Sigma^{\prime}$) T-Morita equivalent if and only if there is a theory $\mathbb{T}^{\prime\prime}$ over a signature $\Sigma^{\prime\prime}$ such that $\Sigma\cap\Sigma^{\prime\prime}=\varnothing$ and $\Sigma^{\prime\prime}$ differs from $\Sigma^{\prime\prime}$ only in renaming the symbols in $\Sigma\cap\Sigma^{\prime}$ (keeping their arities fixed in the case of function and relation symbols) and $\mathbb{T}^{\prime\prime}$ differs from $\mathbb{T}$ only in replacing the symbols in $\Sigma^{\prime}$ with symbols in $\Sigma^{\prime\prime}$ and $\mathbb{T}^{\prime\prime}$ is pre-T-Morita equivalent to $\mathbb{T}$.
Definition 2.1. We call two coherent theories $\mathbb{T}$ and $\mathbb{T}^{\prime}$ J-Morita equivalent if they have equivalent classifying toposes.
Definition 5.3. Let $M\in{\mathcal{C}}$. A solution ring for $M$ is a ${\mathcal{C}}$-algebra $R$ such that the morphism $\varepsilon_{M_{R}}:\iota_{R}\left((M_{R})^{{\mathcal{C}}_{R}}\right)\to M_{R}% =R\otimes M$ is an isomorphism. A Picard-Vessiot ring for $M$ is a minimal solution ring $R$ which is a simple ${\mathcal{C}}$-algebra, and satisfies $R^{\mathcal{C}}:=\operatorname{End}_{{\mathcal{C}}_{R}}(R)=k$. Here, minimal means that for any solution ring $\tilde{R}\in{\mathcal{C}}$ that admits a monomorphism of ${\mathcal{C}}$-algebras to $R$, this monomorphism is indeed an isomorphism.
Definition 4.1. For a ${\mathcal{C}}$-algebra $R$, the additive right-exact functor $()_{R}:({\mathcal{C}},\otimes)\to({\mathcal{C}}_{R},\otimes_{R}),M\mapsto M_{R% }:=(R\otimes M,\mu_{R}\otimes{\rm id}_{M})$ is called the base change functor. It is even a tensor functor, and it is a left adjoint to the forgetful functor ${\mathcal{C}}_{R}\to{\mathcal{C}}$ (see [13, Thm. 18.2]). We can also base change the functors $\iota$ and $()^{\mathcal{C}}$. In more details, having in mind that $\operatorname{End}_{{\mathcal{C}}_{R}}(R)=\operatorname{Mor}_{\mathcal{C}}(% \mathds{1},R)=R^{\mathcal{C}}$: $\iota_{R}:\mathsf{Mod}_{R^{\mathcal{C}}}\to{\mathcal{C}}_{R},V\mapsto R\otimes% _{\iota(R^{\mathcal{C}})}\iota(V)$ and $()^{{\mathcal{C}}_{R}}:{\mathcal{C}}_{R}\to\mathsf{Mod}_{R^{\mathcal{C}}},M% \mapsto\operatorname{Mor}_{{\mathcal{C}}_{R}}(R,M)=\operatorname{Mor}_{{% \mathcal{C}}}(\mathds{1},M)=M^{\mathcal{C}}.$ A special case is given, if $R=\iota(A)$ for some commutative $k$-algebra $A$. In this case, $\iota_{R}$ is “the same” as $\iota$. This case corresponds to an extension by constants in the theory of differential or difference modules.
Definition 1.23. A bicategory $\mathbb{A}$ consists of the following data: (1) A set of objects $\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{A}\right)$. Elements in $\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{A}\right)$ are sometimes called 0-cells. (2) For any $\left(x,y\right)\in\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{A}\right)\times\mathrm{Ob}\,% \left(\mathbb{A}\right)$, a small category $\mathbb{A}\left(x,y\right)$ which consists of • Objects called 1-cells • Arrows between 1-cells which are called 2-cells. The identity 2-cell for a 1-cell $f$ will be denoted $\widetilde{1_{f}}$. • A composition rule $\tiny\leavevmode\hbox to13.07pt{\vbox to13.07pt{\pgfpicture\makeatletter\hbox t% o 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\definecolor{pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{% 0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@color@rgb@fill% {0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@setlinewidth{0.4pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \nullfont\hbox to 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ } {{}}\hbox{\hbox{{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }{{}{{{}}}{{}}{}{}{}{}{}{}{% }{}{}{{}\pgfsys@moveto{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{4.333252pt}{2.393189% pt}{2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-2.393189pt}{4.3% 33252pt}{-4.333252pt}{2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-4.333252% pt}{-2.393189pt}{-2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{-4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{% 2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{4.333252pt}{-2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}% \pgfsys@closepath\pgfsys@moveto{0.0pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@stroke\pgfsys@invoke{ } }{{{{}}\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@transformcm{1.0}{0.0}{0.0}{1% .0}{-1.874971pt}{-1.249981pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{\definecolor{% pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \pgfsys@color@rgb@fill{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{v}} }}\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope{}{}{}\hss}% \pgfsys@discardpath\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\p