olor}{rgb}{0,0,0}% \pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@color@rgb@fill{0}{0}% {0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@setlinewidth{0.4pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\nullfont\hbox t% o 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ } {{}}\hbox{\hbox{{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }{{}{{{}}}{{}}{}{}{}{}{}{}{% }{}{}{{}\pgfsys@moveto{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{4.333252pt}{2.393189% pt}{2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-2.393189pt}{4.3% 33252pt}{-4.333252pt}{2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-4.333252% pt}{-2.393189pt}{-2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{-4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{% 2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{4.333252pt}{-2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}% \pgfsys@closepath\pgfsys@moveto{0.0pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@stroke\pgfsys@invoke{ } }{{{{}}\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@transformcm{1.0}{0.0}{0.0}{1% .0}{-1.874971pt}{-1.249981pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{\definecolor{% pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \pgfsys@color@rgb@fill{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{h}} }}\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope{}{}{}\hss}% \pgfsys@discardpath\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope\hss}% \lxSVG@closescope\endpgfpicture}}\normalsize\ \alpha$ (4) For any object $x\in\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{A}\right)$, a functor $I_{x}\colon\textbf{1}\to\mathbb{A}\left(x,x\right)$ which identifies a special, “almost identity” 1-cell, $1_{x}$. (5) Additionally, we have some natural isomorphisms on certain products of functors which tell us how our functors $\tiny\leavevmode\hbox to13.07pt{\vbox to13.07pt{\pgfpicture\makeatletter\hbox t% o 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\definecolor{pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{% 0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@color@rgb@fill% {0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@setlinewidth{0.4pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \nullfont\hbox to 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ } {{}}\hbox{\hbox{{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }{{}{{{}}}{{}}{}{}{}{}{}{}{% }{}{}{{}\pgfsys@moveto{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{4.333252pt}{2.393189% pt}{2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-2.393189pt}{4.3% 33252pt}{-4.333252pt}{2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-4.333252% pt}{-2.393189pt}{-2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{-4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{% 2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{4.333252pt}{-2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}% \pgfsys@closepath\pgfsys@moveto{0.0pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@stroke\pgfsys@invoke{ } }{{{{}}\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@transformcm{1.0}{0.0}{0.0}{1% .0}{-1.874971pt}{-1.249981pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{\definecolor{% pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \pgfsys@color@rgb@fill{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{h}} }}\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope{}{}{}\hss}% \pgfsys@discardpath\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope\hss}% \lxSVG@closescope\endpgfpicture}}{}_{xyz}$ work with “almost identities” and associativity. For brevity, we omit the diagrams (which may be found in [Lei97]), and only state the important consequences of them: (a) For 1-cells $f,g,h$ such that $\left(hg\right)f$ and hence $h\left(gf\right)$ are well-defined, we have a 2-cell isomorphism $A_{hgf}\colon\left(hg\right)f\to h\left(gf\right)$. This 2-cell isomorphism (or 2-isomorphism) is called the associator of hgf. (b) For a 1-cell $f\in\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{A}\right)\left(x,y\right)$, we have a 2-isomorphism $r_{f}\colon f\circ 1_{x}\to f$. This 2-isomorphism is called the right unitor of f. (c) For a 1-cell $g\in\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{A}\right)\left(y,x\right)$, we have a 2-isomorphism $\ell_{f}\colon 1_{x}\circ f\to f$. This 2-isomorphism is called the left unitor of f.
Definition 2.3. If a category $\mathbb{A}$ admits both a weighting $k^{\bullet}$ and coweighting $k_{\bullet}$ then its Euler characteristic is $\chi\left({\mathbb{A}}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}k^{a_{i}}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}k_{a_{i}}$.
Definition 1.12. A skeleton or skeletal subcategory $\mathbb{A}_{o}$ of $\mathbb{A}$ is a full subcategory whose object set is a set of representatives of the isomorphism classes of $\mathbb{A}$.
Definition 3.3. The standard n-simplex $\Delta_{n}$ is the topological space given by the set $\left\{\left(x_{0},x_{1},...,x_{n}\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{n+1}|\sum_{i=0}^{n}x_{% i}=\allowbreak 1,x_{i}\geq 0\right\}$ under $\mathbb{R}^{n+1}$’s Euclidean subspace topology.
Definition 1.28. A modification $\Gamma$ between transformations $\sigma$ and $\sigma^{\prime}$ (from a morphism $F\colon\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{B}$ to a morphism $G\colon\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{B}$) is a collection of 2-cells $\Gamma_{x}\colon\sigma_{x}\Rightarrow\sigma^{\prime}_{x}$ for each $x\in\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{A}\right)$. Additionally, for any $f\colon x\to y$, the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix@=5em{&Gf\circ\sigma_{x}\ar[d]_{\sigma_{f}}\ar[r]^{1\tiny\leavevmode% \hbox to13.07pt{\vbox to13.07pt{\pgfpicture\makeatletter\hbox to 0.0pt{% \pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\definecolor{pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{0,0,0}% \pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@color@rgb@fill{0}{0}% {0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@setlinewidth{0.4pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\nullfont\hbox t% o 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ } {{}}\hbox{\hbox{{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }{{}{{{}}}{{}}{}{}{}{}{}{}{% }{}{}{{}\pgfsys@moveto{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{4.333252pt}{2.393189% pt}{2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-2.393189pt}{4.3% 33252pt}{-4.333252pt}{2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-4.333252% pt}{-2.393189pt}{-2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{-4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{% 2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{4.333252pt}{-2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}% \pgfsys@closepath\pgfsys@moveto{0.0pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@stroke\pgfsys@invoke{ } }{{{{}}\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@transformcm{1.0}{0.0}{0.0}{1% .0}{-1.874971pt}{-1.249981pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{\definecolor{% pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \pgfsys@color@rgb@fill{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{h}} }}\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope{}{}{}\hss}% \pgfsys@discardpath\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope\hss}% \lxSVG@closescope\endpgfpicture}}\normalsize\Gamma_{x}}&Gf\circ\sigma^{\prime}% _{x}\ar[d]^{\sigma^{\prime}f}&\inner@par&\sigma_{y}\circ Ff\ar[r]^{\Gamma_{y}% \tiny\leavevmode\hbox to13.07pt{\vbox to13.07pt{\pgfpicture\makeatletter\hbox t% o 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\definecolor{pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{% 0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@color@rgb@fill% {0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@setlinewidth{0.4pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \nullfont\hbox to 0.0pt{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ } {{}}\hbox{\hbox{{\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }{{}{{{}}}{{}}{}{}{}{}{}{}{% }{}{}{{}\pgfsys@moveto{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{4.333252pt}{2.393189% pt}{2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-2.393189pt}{4.3% 33252pt}{-4.333252pt}{2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@curveto{-4.333252% pt}{-2.393189pt}{-2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{0.0pt}{-4.333252pt}\pgfsys@curveto{% 2.393189pt}{-4.333252pt}{4.333252pt}{-2.393189pt}{4.333252pt}{0.0pt}% \pgfsys@closepath\pgfsys@moveto{0.0pt}{0.0pt}\pgfsys@stroke\pgfsys@invoke{ } }{{{{}}\pgfsys@beginscope\pgfsys@invoke{ }\pgfsys@transformcm{1.0}{0.0}{0.0}{1% .0}{-1.874971pt}{-1.249981pt}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{\definecolor{% pgfstrokecolor}{rgb}{0,0,0}\pgfsys@color@rgb@stroke{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }% \pgfsys@color@rgb@fill{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{h}} }}\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope{}{}{}\hss}% \pgfsys@discardpath\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope\hss}% \lxSVG@closescope\endpgfpicture}}\normalsize 1}&\sigma^{\prime}y\circ Ff}$
Definition 3.5. A simplicial set X is a functor $X\colon\Delta^{op}\to\mathbf{Set}$
Definition 1.26. A morphism $F\colon\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{B}$ between bicategories $\mathbb{A}$ and $\mathbb{B}$ consists of the following data: (1) An object function $F_{0}\colon\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{A}\right)\to\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{B% }\right)$ (2) For each pair $\left(x,y\right)\in\mathrm{Ob}\,\left(\mathbb{A}\right)\times\mathrm{Ob}\,% \left(\mathbb{A}\right)$, a functor $F_{xy}\colon\mathbb{A}\left(x,y\right)\to\mathbb{B}\left(F_{0}\left(x\right),F% _{0}\left(y\right)\right)$. and respects “composition” in the following sense (1) There is a 2-cell $\phi_{gf}$ in $\mathbb{A}\left(F_{0}\left(x\right),F_{0}\left(z\right)\right)$ between $F_{yz}\left(g\right)\circ F_{xy}\left(f\right)$ and $F_{xz}\left(g\circ f\right)$. (2) There is a 2-cell $\phi_{x}$ in $\mathbb{A}\left(F_{0}\left(x\right),F_{0}\left(x\right)\right)$ between $I^{\prime}_{F_{0}\left(x\right)}$, the almost-identity 1-cell in $F_{0}\left(x\right)$, and $F_{0}\left(I_{x}\right)$.
Definition 2.16. If a bicategory $\mathbb{A}$ admits both a weighting $k^{\bullet}$ and coweighting $k_{\bullet}$ then its Euler characteristic is $\chi\left({\mathbb{A}}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}k^{a_{i}}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}k_{a_{i}}$.
Definition 1.20. A natural isomorphism $\eta$ is a collection of isomorphisms in $\mathrm{Hom}\left(\mathbb{B}\right)$ that essentially tells us that two functors are the same ($F\cong G$). More formally, two functors $F\colon\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{B}$ and $G\colon\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{B}$ are naturally isomorphic if, for any two objects $x,y$ in $\mathbb{A}$, we have morphisms $\eta_{x}\colon F\left(x\right)\to G\left(x\right)$ and $\eta_{y}\colon F\left(y\right)\to G\left(y\right)$ such that, for any morphism $f\colon x\to y$, the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix@=5em{&F\left(x\right)\ar[d]_{F\left(f\right)}\ar[r]^{\eta_{x}}&G% \left(x\right)\ar[d]^{G\left(f\right)}&\inner@par&F\left(y\right)\ar[r]^{\eta_% {y}}&G\left(y\right)}$ i.e. $\eta_{y}\circ F\left(f\right)=G\left(f\right)\circ\eta_{x}$ for all $f\colon x\to y$.
Definition 2.1. The adjacency matrix of a finite category $\mathbb{A}$ under some total ordering $\left\{a_{1},a_{2},...,a_{n}\right\}$ is $\emph{M}\left(\mathbb{A}\right)=\begin{bmatrix}|\mathrm{Hom}\left(a_{1},a_{1}% \right)|&\dots&|\mathrm{Hom}\left(a_{1},a_{n}\right)|\\ \vdots&\ddots&\vdots\\ |\mathrm{Hom}\left(a_{n},a_{1}\right)|&\dots&|\mathrm{Hom}\left(a_{n},a_{n}% \right)|\end{bmatrix}.$
